{{ill|Sashikuni Ōkami|lt=Sashikuni Ōkami|ja|刺国大神|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Sashikuni_Okami|8=fr|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (刺国大神) was a Japanese deity associated with {{ill|Susanoo|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the [[Izumo Province|Izumo Province]].<ref name="fountainhead" />{{rp|278}}<ref name=":0" />

He's the father of {{ill|Sashikuni Wakahime|ja|刺国若比売|1=Sashikuni Wakahime|2=ja|3=刺国若比売|4=simple|5=User:Immanuelle/Sashikuni Wakahime|qq=draft|en:draft||simple|User:Immanuelle/Sashikuni Wakahime|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<ref name="fountainhead">{{cite book |last=Herbert |first=J. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sg_JBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT402 |title=Shinto: At the Fountainhead of Japan |publisher=Taylor & Francis |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-136-90376-2 |series=Routledge Library Editions: Japan |page=402 |access-date=2020-11-21}}</ref>{{rp|278}}<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Sashikuniō • . A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史|url=https://historyofjapan.co.uk/wiki/sashikunio/|access-date=2024-03-22|website=. A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史|language=en-GB}}</ref>.

The Sashikuni in his name refers to land marking.<ref name=":0" /> This makes him analogous to {{ill|Michikaeshi Ōkami|lt=Michikaeshi|en|4=ja|5=道祖神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

