'''Sasikuni Ōkami''' (刺国大神/サシクニオオノカミ, {{smaller|[[Historical Kana Usage|historical kana]]:}} サシクニオホノカミ) is a {{ill|deity|ja|神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} from {{ill|Japanese mythology|ja|日本神話|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The deity is also referred to as '''Sasikushifutohime''' (佐志久斯布刀比士).

In the *Kojiki*, Sasikuni Ōkami is mentioned by name as the parent (father) of {{ill|Sasikuni Wakabime|ja|刺国若比売|1=Sashikuni Wakahime|2=ja|3=刺国若比売|4=simple|5=User:Immanuelle/Sashikuni Wakahime|qq=draft}}. In the records of {{ill|Awaga Shrine|ja|米鵠神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (*Awaga Daimyōjin Genki*), the deity is referred to as Sasikushifutohime.

The name "Sasu" (刺す) is interpreted as "marking" or "staking out" a boundary, signifying ownership. "Ō" (大) denotes the status of being a parent in relation to {{ill|Sasikuni Wakabime|ja|刺国若比売|1=Sashikuni Wakahime|2=ja|3=刺国若比売|4=simple|5=User:Immanuelle/Sashikuni Wakahime|qq=draft}}. Thus, the name is understood to mean "the parent who claims the land"{{Sfn|Nishinomiya|2014|p=373}}.

== Genealogy ==
[[File:Susanowo family tree.png|thumb|250px|The genealogy from {{ill|Susanoo|ja|須佐之田生命|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主|qq=draft|qq=draft}} as depicted in the *Kojiki*. Male deities are shown in blue, and female deities in red.]]
Sasikuni Ōkami is identified as the father of {{ill|Sasikuni Wakabime|ja|刺国若比売|1=Sashikuni Wakahime|2=ja|3=刺国若比売|4=simple|5=User:Immanuelle/Sashikuni Wakahime|qq=draft}}, who gave birth to {{ill|Ameno Fuyukoromo no Kami|ja|天之冬衣神|1=Ame-no-Fuyukinu|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主|qq=draft|qq=draft}} through {{ill|Omizunu no Kami|ja|水童神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== Title ==
{{ill|Sashikuni Ōkami|lt=Sashikuni Ōkami|ja|刺国大神|en:draft|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Sashikuni_Okami|8=fr|qq=draft|qq=draft}} has the distinction of being one of only seven {{ill|kami|en}} to be honored with the title '''Ōkami''' ({{CJKV|j=大神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) or "Great Kami"; the other six are [[Izanagi|Izanagi]], {{ill|Izanami|lt=Izanami|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Dōsojin|lt=Michikaeshi|en|4=ja|5=道祖神|6=fr|7=Dōsojin|8=en:draft|9=Michikaeshi Ōkami|10=simple|11=User:Immanuelle/Dōsojin|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (also known as Yomido ni sayarimasu ōkami (?) who is the kami of the great rock used by Izanagi to obstruct the way to Yomi, and thus, preventing emergence of evil spirits from the Underworld), {{ill|Sarutahiko Ōkami|lt=Sarutahiko|en|4=fr|6=simple|7=User:Immanuelle/Sarutahiko Ōkami|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Inari Ōkami|lt=Inari|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Amaterasu|en}}. Sarutahiko and Inari appear to be the only Okami from the ''kunitsukami'', or earthly kami, the others being ''{{ill|Amatsukami|en|4=fr|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'' (heavenly deities). Although there is some other Daimyōjin and Daigongen, most of them appeared later in the History of Japanese Religion, such as [[Hachiman]] (deification of [[Empress Jingū|Empress Jingu]], [[Emperor Ōjin|Emperor Ojin]] and maybe [[Takenouchi no Sukune]], as a successful head of state) or Hindu deities, the meaning of Daimyōjin appear to be a little different from Ōkami, the latter being obviously more ancient. <ref>{{Cite web|title=Kami – OCCULT WORLD|url=https://occult-world.com/kami/|access-date=2024-03-19|language=en-US}}</ref>{{Better source}}

